  "prompt": "How did Instagram get its first 25,000 signups?",
  "response": "Instagram's early growth was primarily driven by its founders, Kevin Systrom and Mike Krieger, leveraging their network and strategic launch tactics. Here are some key details about their initial user acquisition:\n\n1. Exclusive, invite-only launch\n- They initially launched the app as a limited, invite-only platform\n- This created a sense of exclusivity and buzz around the app\n\n2. Leveraging tech and startup networks\n- Systrom had connections in the Silicon Valley startup scene\n- They first shared the app with tech influencers and early adopters\n- These initial users helped spread the word through their networks\n\n3. Launch at SXSW Interactive\n- They strategically launched the app during the SXSW conference in 2010\n- This tech-focused event helped them reach early tech enthusiasts\n\n4. Integration with other social platforms\n- Users could easily share Instagram photos on Twitter and Facebook\n- This cross-platform sharing helped drive initial user growth\n\n5. Unique photo filters and editing features\n- The app's innovative photo editing tools were a major draw\n- Users were excited about transforming their smartphone photos\n\nWhile precise details of their first 25,000 signups aren't publicly documented, these strategies were crucial in their early user acquisition and rapid initial growth.",
